ering its position quite fragile. Garsten and Sörbom argue that the WEF must be viewed relationally as a brokering organization that lives between the market and political spheres and that extends its reach through associated individuals and groups.They place the WEF in the context of a broader shift, arguing that while this type of governance opens up novel ways of dealing with urgent global problems, it challenges core democratic values.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aInternational economic relations. 0aInternational relations. 4aWorld Economic Forum. 4adiscretionary. 4aglobal governance. 4amarkets. 4aseduction. 4astatus. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Government & Business.2bisacsh1 aSörbom, Adrienne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360605040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606050423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503606050.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles